  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 34.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Awake to righteousness.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The word rendered \"awake\" means \"awake at once from a drunken sleep.\" This verb does not occur elsewhere in the New Testament. The word rendered \"awake\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 5:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 13:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is a different one. The metaphor, however, occurs in the simple verb in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Thessalonians 5:6, 8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 5:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. The word rendered \"to righteousness\" is literally an adverb, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "righteously.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " It may mean \"as is fit.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And sin not.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Here the present tense, \"be not sinning,\" is contrasted with the instantaneous aorist, \"awake.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Have not the knowledge.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The original is stronger, \"have an ignorance.\" They have not a vacuum of nescience, but a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "plenuum",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of ignorance. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "I speak this to your shame;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "I am speaking to shame you.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The object of all I am saying is to excite your shame - not, as in some previous instances, \"to spare you.\" 1 Corinthians 15:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Awake (ἐκνήψατε)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Only here in the New Testament. It means to awake from a drunken stupor. Compare Joel 1:5, Sept. The kindred verb ἀνανήφω return to soberness (A.V. and Rev., recover), occurs at 2 Timothy 2:26.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Only here in the New Testament. It means to awake from a drunken stupor. Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Joel 1:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", Sept. The kindred verb ἀνανήφω return to soberness (A.V. and Rev., recover), occurs at ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Timothy 2:26",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Have not the knowledge (ἀγνωσίαν ἔχουσιν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., have an ignorance. Stronger than ἀγνοεῖν to be ignorant. They have and hold it. For the form of expression, see on have sorrow, John 16:29. The word for ignorance is found only here and 1 Peter 2:15 (see note). ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Lit., have an ignorance. Stronger than ἀγνοεῖν to be ignorant. They have and hold it. For the form of expression, see on have sorrow, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 16:29",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The word for ignorance is found only here and ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Peter 2:15",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (see note). ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
]